      <hedline>
        <hl1>Ask an American</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Menachem Rosenberg letter on Bernard Holland's August 20 column on Riccardo Muti holds New York Philharmonic should appoint American-born conductor (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The right thing for the New York Philharmonic is to appoint an American-born conductor as its music director. There are several in this country with the requisite musical depth and experience. They might even do the job for a lot less than a $2 million salary.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The right thing for the New York Philharmonic is to appoint an American-born conductor as its music director. There are several in this country with the requisite musical depth and experience. They might even do the job for a lot less than a $2 million salary.</p>
        <p>Great American orchestras like the New York Philharmonic have the responsibility to provide a platform to showcase talented American-born conductors and give them the opportunity to develop an international reputation. Leonard Bernstein was given such an opportunity at a time when his musicianship and experience as a conductor were less than that of current eligible American conductors. We should give another American such a chance.</p>
        <p>MENACHEM ROSENBERG  Brooklyn</p>
        <p>RICCARDO MUTI</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
